entry.title: Acacia suaveolens, Epacris impressa var. impressa
Epacris impressa var. impressa
entry.content: Mass displays of white Epacris impressa growing with pink Epacris in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath - see pic 4. In other places there are pink Epacris and white L. virgatus growing en masse but here L. virgatus seems to have been replaced by white Epacris.

entry.title: Acacia suaveolens
entry.content: Occasional mass flowering on roadsides, especially in gullies. Here plants were 2m+ along roadside, occasionally broken up with pink Epacris impressa.

entry.title: Leucopogon virgatus var. virgatus
entry.content: Mass displays of L. virgatus growing with pink (no white) Epacris impressa in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath. In other places there are pink and white Epacris growing en masse but here L. virgatus seems to have displaced white Epacris.

entry.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
entry.content: Magnificent displays of Epacris in this SW corner of Anglesea Heath. At this location the Epacris were all red and mass flowering with Leucopogon virgatus, Acacia suaveolens and with Banksia marginata sprinked through.

entry.title: Astroloma humifusum, Cassytha glabella f. dispar
Lepidosperma filiforme
entry.content: Leaf and stem similar and terete.

entry.title: Stylidium graminifolium s.s.
entry.content: Leaves were quite wide at maybe 3.1mm wide.

entry.title: Hakea ulicina
entry.content: Leaf width would suggest H. repullulans but the signs of vegetative new growth on the second pic means it can only be H. ulicina.
